# Error Handling Patterns

Handle errors explicitly. Use custom error classes. Provide graceful degradation. Never swallow errors silently.

---

## Triggers

**APPLY WHEN:** Writing error handling code, implementing error boundaries, designing failure modes.
**SKIP WHEN:** Code has no failure paths or delegates entirely to framework.

---

## Core Directive

**Handle errors at boundaries** - Validate at entry points. Propagate to appropriate handlers. Never use empty catch blocks.

---

## Try/Catch Best Practices

**Always handle or rethrow; never swallow:**

```typescript
// Good: Explicit handling
async function loadData() {
  try {
    const data = await fetchData();
    return process(data);
  } catch (error) {
    logError(error);
    showUserMessage("Unable to load data. Please try again.");
    return getEmptyFallback();
  }
}

// Good: Rethrow with context
try {
  await saveUser(user);
} catch (error) {
  throw new Error(`Failed to save user ${user.id}`, { cause: error });
}

// Bad: Silent swallow
try {
  await riskyOperation();
} catch (e) {
  // Ignored - no logging, no fallback
}
```

